entity.p: Xingguo County (simplified Chinese: 兴国县; traditional Chinese: 興國縣; pinyin: Xīngguó Xiàn) is a county in south central Jiangxi province, People's Republic of China. It is under the administration of and located in the north of the prefecture-level city of Ganzhou, with a total area of 3,214.46 km2 (1,241.11 sq mi). Its population was 719,830 at the 2010 census.[2]

The Xinghai Conservatory of Music, also known as the Xinghai Conservatory is a music conservatory in the Tianhe District of Guangzhou City, Guangdong Province, southern China. It was established in 1932 by the composer Ma Sicong as the Guangzhou Conservatory of Music.

Xinghai County (simplified Chinese: 兴海县; traditional Chinese: 興海縣; pinyin: Xīnghǎi Xiàn; Tibetan: བྲག་དཀར་རྫོང་།, Wylie: brag dkar rdzong) is county under the jurisdiction of Hainan Tibetan Autonomous Prefecture, in the east-central part of Qinghai Province, People's Republic of China

Xinghe County (Mongolian: ᠰᠢᠩᠾᠧ ᠰᠢᠶᠠᠨ Siŋhė siyan, Шинхэ шянь; simplified Chinese: 兴和县; traditional Chinese: 興和縣; pinyin: Xīnghé Xiàn) is a county of south-central Inner Mongolia, People's Republic of China, bordering the provinces of Hebei to the east and Shanxi to the south. It is under the administration of Ulaan Chab City, and is situated on the China National Highway 110 between Ulaan Chab and Zhangjiakou in Hebei province. Bordering county-level divisions include Fengzhen City to the southwest, Chahar Right Front Banner to the west, Chahar Right Back Banner to the northwest, and Shangdu County to the north.

Xinghua (simplified Chinese: 兴华; traditional Chinese: 興華; pinyin: Xīnghuá) is a town of Luoning County in western Henan province, China,[1] located 24 kilometres (15 mi) southwest of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has 12 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua (simplified Chinese: 兴化; traditional Chinese: 興化; pinyin: Xīnghuà) is a county-level city under the administration of Taizhou, Jiangsu province, China. It is located in the central part of Jiangsu Province. It borders the prefecture-level cities of Yancheng to the north and east and Yangzhou to the west.

Xinghua (simplified Chinese: 兴华镇; traditional Chinese: 興華鎮; pinyin: Xīnghuá Zhèn) is a town under the administration of Meihekou City in southwestern Jilin province, China,[1] located about 40 kilometres (25 mi) northeast of downtown just off of G1212 Shenyang–Jilin Expressway. As of 2011[update], it has eight villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua (simplified Chinese: 兴华; traditional Chinese: 興華; pinyin: Xīnghuá) is a town of Qinggang County in western Heilongjiang province, China,[1] located 39 kilometres (24 mi) north-northeast of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has 12 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Road Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华路街道; traditional Chinese: 興華路街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Lù Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of the city of Gaobeidian, Hebei, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has 19 residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Sui Ethnic Township (simplified Chinese: 兴华水族乡; traditional Chinese: 興華水族鄉; pinyin: Xīnghuá Shuǐzú Xiāng) is a township of southern Rongjiang County in southeastern Guizhou province, China,[1] located about 37 kilometres (23 mi) southwest of the county seat at an elevation of 331 m (1,086 ft), which is low-lying for Guizhou's standards. As of 2011[update], it has nine villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Ganjingzi District, Dalian, People's Republic of China,[1] located to the east of Dalian Zhoushuizi International Airport. As of 2011[update], it has 13 residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴化街道; traditional Chinese: 興化街道; pinyin: Xīnghuà Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Longfeng District, in the south of Daqing, Heilongjiang, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has six residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Changyi District, Jilin City, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has six residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (Chinese: 杏花街道; pinyin: Xìnghuā Jiēdào; literally: 'apricot blossom') is a subdistrict of Chengzihe District, in the northeastern suburbs of Jixi, Heilongjiang, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has two residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Manzhouli, Inner Mongolia, China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has three residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Xinxing District, Qitaihe, Heilongjiang, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has two residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Tiexi District, Shenyang, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has six residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict of Wanbailin District, Taiyuan, Shanxi, People's Republic of China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has ten residential communities (社区) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Subdistrict (simplified Chinese: 兴华街道; traditional Chinese: 興華街道; pinyin: Xīnghuá Jiēdào) is a subdistrict and the seat of Zhalantun, Inner Mongolia, China.[1] As of 2011[update], it has five residential communities (居委会) under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Township (simplified Chinese: 兴华乡; traditional Chinese: 興華鄉; pinyin: Xīnghuá Xiāng) is a township of Baiquan County in western Heilongjiang province, China,[1] located about 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) due north of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has eight villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Township (simplified Chinese: 兴华乡; traditional Chinese: 興華鄉; pinyin: Xīnghuá Xiāng) is a township of Huma County in the east of Da Hinggan Ling Prefecture in far northern Heilongjiang province, China,[1] located about 63 kilometres (39 mi) northwest of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has six villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Township (simplified Chinese: 兴化乡; traditional Chinese: 興化鄉; pinyin: Xīnghuà Xiāng) is a township of Liangdang County in southeastern Gansu province, China,[1] located 7.2 kilometres (4.5 mi) southeast of the county seat and 8.1 km (5.0 mi) west of the border with Shaanxi. As of 2011[update], it has 10 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinghua Township (simplified Chinese: 兴化乡; traditional Chinese: 興化鄉; pinyin: Xīnghuà Xiāng) is a township of Tanchang County in southeastern Gansu province, China,[1] located 18 kilometres (11 mi) northeast of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has eight villages under its administration.[2]

Xingjing (simplified Chinese: 兴泾; traditional Chinese: 興涇; pinyin: Xīngjīng) is a town under the administration of Xixia District, Yinchuan, Ningxia, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 3 residential communities and 6 villages under its administration.[2]

The Xingkang Bridge or Luding Yaye Expressway Bridge as is a suspension bridge in Luding County, Sichuan, China that opened in 2018. The 285 m (935 ft) high deck is one of the highest in world. The bridge forms part of the G4218 Ya'an–Kargilik Expressway carrying traffic over the Dadu River. The bridge began construction in 2014 and opened in 2018. The main span of the bridge is 1,100 m (3,600 ft) making it one of the longest ever built.

Xinglong County (simplified Chinese: 兴隆县; traditional Chinese: 興隆縣; pinyin: Xīnglóng Xiàn) is a county in the northeast of Hebei province, bordering the municipalities of Beijing to the west and Tianjin to the southwest. It is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Chengde, with a population of 320,000[when?] residing in an area of 3,116 km2 (1,203 sq mi).

Xinglongtai District (simplified Chinese: 兴隆台区; traditional Chinese: 興隆台區; pinyin: Xīnglóngtái Qū) is a district under the administration of the city of Panjin, Liaoning province, People's Republic of China. It has a total area of 194 square kilometres (75 sq mi) with many small exclaves in other districts, and a population of approximately 370,000 people.[when?] The district's postal code is 124010, and the district government is located on Shiyou Street.

Xingqing District (simplified Chinese: 兴庆区; traditional Chinese: 興慶區; pinyin: Xīngqìng Qū; Wade–Giles: Hsin-ch’ing Ch’ü, Xiao'erjing: سٍ شٍ ﺛُﻮْ‎) is one of 3 urban districts of the prefecture-level city of Yinchuan, the capital of Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, Northwest China, bordering Inner Mongolia to the east. It has a total area of 757.6 km2 (292.5 sq mi), and, according to the 2010 China Census, a population of 678,306 people.[1]

Xingren (simplified Chinese: 兴仁市; traditional Chinese: 興仁市; pinyin: Xīngrén Shì) is a county-level city of southwestern Guizhou province, China. It is under the administration of the Qianxinan Buyei and Miao Autonomous Prefecture.

Xingshan County (simplified Chinese: 兴山县; traditional Chinese: 興山縣; pinyin: Xīngshān Xiàn) is a county of western Hubei, People's Republic of China. It is under the administration of Yichang Prefecture-level City.

The county occupies the mountainous north-western corner of Yichang prefecture ("prefecture-level city"), bordering on Badong County in the west and Shennongjia in the north. The highest mountains within the county are Mount Wanchao (2,253 metres (7,392 ft) elevation) and Mount Wanfu (1,819 metres (5,968 ft)).

Xingtai (simplified Chinese: 邢台; traditional Chinese: 邢臺 or 邢台; pinyin: Xíngtái; Wade–Giles: Hsing2-tai2) is a prefecture-level city in southern Hebei province, People's Republic of China. It has a total area of 12,486 square kilometres (4,821 sq mi) and administers 2 districts, 2 county-level cities and 15 counties. At the 2010 census, its population was 7,104,103 inhabitants whom 1,461,809 lived in the built-up (or metro) area made of 2 urban districts and Xingtai and Nanhe Counties largely being conurbated now. It borders Shijiazhuang and Hengshui in the north, Handan in the south, and the provinces of Shandong and Shanxi in the east and west respectively.

Xingtai is the oldest city in North China.[citation needed] The history of Xingtai can be traced back 3500 years ago. During the Shang Dynasty, Xingtai functioned as a capital city. During the Zhou Dynasty, the State of Xing – from which the present name derives – was founded in the city. During the Warring States period, the state of Zhao made Xingtai its provisional capital. The city was known as Xindu for most of the Qin Dynasty, but after the 207 BC Battle of Julu (within present-day Pingxiang County, not today's Julu County), it became known as Xiangguo. During the Sixteen Kingdoms Period, when the Later Zhao was founded by Shi Le of the Jie, the capital was again at Xiangguo. During the Sui and Tang dynasties, the city was known as Xingzhou. During the Yuan Dynasty, Ming, and Qing dynasties, Xingtai was called Shunteh (Shundefu) and functioned as a prefecture in China.

Xingtai (simplified Chinese: 邢台; traditional Chinese: 邢臺 or 邢台; pinyin: Xíngtái; Wade–Giles: Hsing2-tai2) is a prefecture-level city in southern Hebei province, People's Republic of China. It has a total area of 12,486 square kilometres (4,821 sq mi) and administers 2 districts, 2 county-level cities and 15 counties. At the 2010 census, its population was 7,104,103 inhabitants whom 1,461,809 lived in the built-up (or metro) area made of 2 urban districts and Xingtai and Nanhe Counties largely being conurbated now. It borders Shijiazhuang and Hengshui in the north, Handan in the south, and the provinces of Shandong and Shanxi in the east and west respectively.

Xingtai Dalian Airport (Chinese: 邢台褡裢机场) (IATA: XNT, ICAO: ZBXT) is an airport serving the city of Xingtai in Hebei Province, China. It is located near the town of Dalian (Chinese: 褡裢) 15 kilometers from the city center. It is mainly a military airport, but the airport also served commercial flights between 1993 and 2001.[2] In 2011 the Civil Aviation Administration of China approved the 300 million yuan expansion plan for the airport, and it is expected to resume commercial service within five years. At the present time, the city was served by Jinan Yaoqiang International Airport and Shijiazhuang Zhengding International Airport located in the middle of the city. [3]

Xingtang County (simplified Chinese: 行唐县; traditional Chinese: 行唐縣; pinyin: Xíngtáng Xiàn) is a county of Hebei Province, North China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Shijiazhuang, the capital of the province.

Xingtian Temple (Chinese: 行天宮; pinyin: Xíngtiān Gōng; Pe̍h-ōe-jī: Hêng-thian-kiong; also Xingtian Gong or Hsing Tian Kong) is a popular temple in Zhongshan District, Taipei, Taiwan. This temple is devoted to Guan Yu, the patron god of businessmen, and is relatively recent in origin. This temple is situated on a street corner near the center of the city. Sculptures of dragons feature prominently in this temple's design. It covers over 7,000 square meters.[2]

Xingtian Temple (Chinese: 行天宮; pinyin: Xíngtiān Gōng) is a metro station in Taipei, Taiwan served by Taipei Metro. The station opened on 3 November 2010. This station is named after the Xingtian Temple, but others include the Xingtian Temple Market and Songjiang Market are also notable.

The Xingu River (Portuguese: Rio Xingu, Portuguese pronunciation: [ɕĩˈɡu], /ʃiːŋˈɡuː/ sheeng-GOO) is a 1,640 km (1,019 mi)[1] river in north Brazil. It is a southeast tributary of the Amazon River and one of the largest clearwater rivers in the Amazon basin,[2] accounting for about 5% of its water.[3]

Xingwen County (simplified Chinese: 兴文县; traditional Chinese: 興文縣; pinyin: Xīngwén Xiàn) is a county in Yibin, Sichuan, China. It is located in the southern part of Sichuan province and borders Yunnan and Guizhou provinces. It has become known for its Geopark,[1] Xingwen Stoneforest, a Karst landscape.[2]

Xingyang (simplified Chinese: 荥阳; traditional Chinese: 滎陽; pinyin: Xíngyáng), is a county-level city of Henan Province, South Central China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Zhengzhou. It is situated 15 kilometers to the west of Zhengzhou city proper. The population of Xingyang is around 590,000 and the area of Xingyang is about 908 km2 (351 sq mi).[1]

Xingye County (simplified Chinese: 兴业县; traditional Chinese: 興業縣; pinyin: Xīngyè Xiàn; Zhuang: Hinghyez Yen) is a county in the southeast of Guangxi, China. It is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Yulin.

Xingyi (simplified Chinese: 兴义; traditional Chinese: 興義; pinyin: Xīngyì) is a county-level city administered by the Qianxinan Buyei and Miao Autonomous Prefecture, in the southwest of Guizhou Province, China.

Xingyun Lake (Chinese: 星云湖; pinyin: Xīngyún Hú) also known as Jiangchuan Sea (Chinese: 江川海子; pinyin: Jiāngchuān Hǎizi), is a plateau lake in Yunnan Province, southwest of China. The Xingyun Lake and the Fuxian Lake are separated by a mountain and linked by a river.[1] The lake has a total area of about 34.71 square kilometers. The average depth is 5.3 m, with an elevation of 1722 m. the water storage capacity is about 1.84×108m3.[2]

The Xingó Dam is a concrete face rock-fill dam on the São Francisco River on the border of Alagoas and Sergipe, near Piranhas, Brazil. The dam was built for navigation, water supply and hydroelectric power generation as it supports a 3,162 megawatts (4,240,000 hp) power station. It was constructed between 1987 and 1994 and the last of its generators was commissioned in 1997. In Portuguese, the dam is called the Usina Hidrelétrica de Xingó.

Xinhe (Chinese: 新河; pinyin: Xīnhé; literally: 'new river') is a county in the south of Hebei province, China, located on the Fuyang River (滏阳河), which is part of the Hai River watershed. It is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Xingtai, with a population of 170,000[when?] residing in an area of 366 km2 (141 sq mi). The county is served by G20 Qingdao–Yinchuan Expressway and China National Highway 308.

Xinhe County (Chinese: 新和县) as the official romanized name, also transliterated from Uyghur as Toksu County (Uyghur: توقسۇ ناھىيىسى‎; Chinese: 托克苏县), is a county in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region, and is under the administration of the Aksu Prefecture. It contains an area of 5,821 km2 (2,248 sq mi). According to the 2002 census, it has a population of 140,000.

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Dongshan District, Hegang, Heilongjiang, People's Republic of China,[1] located 23 kilometres (14 mi) south of downtown Hegang near the border with neighbouring Jiamusi City. As of 2011[update], it has one residential community (社区) and 10 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Linze County in west-central Gansu province, China,[1] located 47 kilometres (29 mi) northwest of Zhangye and serviced by China National Highway 312; G30 Lianyungang–Khorgas Expressway passes just to the town's south. As of 2011[update], it has 11 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Tongyu County in northwestern Jilin province, China,[1] located 29 kilometres (18 mi) southwest of the county seat and about half that northwest of the border with Inner Mongolia. As of 2011[update], it has one residential community (居委会) and 14 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Funing County in southeastern Yunnan province, China,[1] located in the immediate vicinity of the county seat some 143 kilometres (89 mi) east-northeast of Wenshan City; G80 Guangzhou–Kunming Expressway and China National Highway 323. As of 2011[update], it has three residential communities (社区) and nine villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Xuanhan County in northeastern Sichuan province, China,[1] located 50 kilometres (31 mi) northeast of the county seat. As of 2011[update], it has one residential community (社区) and 10 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua County (simplified Chinese: 新化县; traditional Chinese: 新化縣; pinyin: Xīnhuà Xiàn)Vis a county and the 4th most populous county-level division in the Province of Hunan, China; it is under the administration of Loudi City.

Located along the middle reaches of the Zi River, it covers 3,635 square kilometers and has a population of 1,291,626 (2002). Xinhua shares the border with Lengshuijiang, Lianyuan, Xinshao, Xupu and Longhui counties and cities. As a county, it was founded at 1072 (Northern Song Dynasty) and now it is under jurisdiction of the Loudi City and subdivided into 7 townships and 19 towns, Shangmei is the county seat.

Xinhua District (simplified Chinese: 新华区; traditional Chinese: 新華區; pinyin: Xīnhuá Qū; literally: 'New China') is one of eight districts of the prefecture-level city of Shijiazhuang, the capital of Hebei Province, North China, located in the northwest of the urban core of Shijiazhuang.

Xinhua (simplified Chinese: 新华; traditional Chinese: 新華; pinyin: Xīnhuá; literally: 'new China') is a town of Linhe District, Bayannur, Inner Mongolia, People's Republic of China,[1] located 36 kilometres (22 mi) northeast of downtown. As of 2011[update], it has 29 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua Township (simplified Chinese: 新华乡; traditional Chinese: 新華鄉; pinyin: Xīnhuá Xiāng; literally: 'new China') is a township of western Qianjiang District in southeastern Chongqing Municipality, People's Republic of China,[1] located near the border with Pengshui County to the west and about 27 kilometres (17 mi) southwest of the district seat and 200 km (120 mi) east-southeast of downtown Chongqing as the crow flies. As of 2011[update], it has seven villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua Township (simplified Chinese: 新华乡; traditional Chinese: 新華鄉; pinyin: Xīnhuá Xiāng; literally: 'new China') is a township of Liangzhou District, Wuwei, Gansu, People's Republic of China,[1] located more than 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) south-southwest of downtown in the southern foothills of the Qilian Mountains. As of 2011[update], it has 13 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua Township (simplified Chinese: 新华乡; traditional Chinese: 新華鄉; pinyin: Xīnhuá Xiāng; literally: 'new China') is a township of Liuzhi Special District, Liupanshui, Guizhou, People's Republic of China,[1] located more than 65 kilometres (40 mi) south-southeast of downtown as the crow flies. As of 2011[update], it has one residential community (居委会) and nine villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua Township (simplified Chinese: 新华乡; traditional Chinese: 新華鄉; pinyin: Xīnhuá Xiāng; literally: 'new China') is a township of Beilin District, in the western suburbs of Suihua, Heilongjiang, People's Republic of China,[1] located more than 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) west of downtown. As of 2011[update], it has seven villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhua Township (simplified Chinese: 新华乡; traditional Chinese: 新華鄉; pinyin: Xīnhuá Xiāng; literally: 'new China') is a township of Yuanmou County in north-central Yunnan province, China,[1] located about 20 kilometres (12 mi) due west of the county seat and 75 km (47 mi) north-northeast of Chuxiong City as the crow flies. As of 2011[update], it has four villages under its administration.[2]

Xinhuang Dong Autonomous County (simplified Chinese: 新晃侗族自治县; traditional Chinese: 新晃侗族自治縣; pinyin: Xīnhuǎng Dòngzú Zìzhìxiàn; usually referred to as "Xinhuang County", commonly abbreviated as Xinhuang, simplified Chinese: 新晃县; traditional Chinese: 新晃縣; pinyin: Xīnhuǎng Xiàn) is an autonomous county of Dong people and the westernmost county of Hunan Province, China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Huaihua.

On the map, Xinhuang County looks like the insertion of a wedge on the eastern margin of Guizhou Province. It is the westernmost county of the province, the county is surrounded by Guizhou to the north, west and south. it is bordered to the north by Wanshan District of Tongren, to the west by Yuping, Zhenyuan and Sansui Counties, to the north by Tianzhu County, to the east by Zhijiang County. The county covers 1,508 km2 (582 sq mi), as of 2015, it has a census registered population of 258,246 and a permanent resident population of 249,100.[4] The county has 9 towns and 2 townships under its jurisdiction, the county seat is the town of Huangzhou (晃州镇).[5]

Xinhui, alternately romanized as Sunwui[a] and also known as Kuixiang, is an urban district of Jiangmen in Guangdong, China. It grew from a separate city founded at the confluence of the Tan and West Rivers. It has a population of about 735,500,[when?] 98% of whom are Han Chinese but many of whom speak a dialect of Cantonese as their first language. Xinhui is best known in China for its chenpi, a kind of dried Mandarin orange peel.

Xinhui is situated at the confluence of the Tan and West Rivers in the southwestern area of the Pearl River Delta.[5] It borders the South China Sea and adjoins Macao and Hong Kong. It comprises a total area of 1,387.02 square meters (14,929.8 sq ft).[verification needed] Geologists have shown that Xinhui originated as a shallow bay at the mouth of the Pearl River about 5000 years ago, with its southeastern portion consisting of a chain of islands. The movement of the Tan and West Rivers eventually formed a delta that became the present alluvial plain over the course of the last nine hundred years.

Xining (simplified Chinese: 西宁; traditional Chinese: 西寧 Xīníng [ɕí.nǐŋ]; Standard Tibetan: ཟི་ལིང་། Ziling) is the capital of Qinghai province in western China,[3] and the largest city on the Tibetan Plateau. It has 2,208,708 inhabitants at the 2010 census of whom 1,198,304 live in the built up area made of 4 urban districts.[4]

The city was a commercial hub along the Northern Silk Road's Hexi Corridor for over 2000 years, and was a stronghold of the Han, Sui, Tang, and Song dynasties' resistance against nomadic attacks from the west. Although long a part of Gansu province, Xining was added to Qinghai in 1928. Xining holds sites of religious significance to Muslims and Buddhists, including the Dongguan Mosque and Ta'er Monastery. The city lies in the Huangshui River valley, and owing to its high altitude, has a cold semi-arid climate. It is connected by rail to Lhasa, Tibet and connected by high-speed rail to Lanzhou, Gansu and Ürümqi, Xinjiang.

Xining Caojiabao International Airport (IATA: XNN, ICAO: ZLXN), also called Caojiapu Airport, is an airport serving Xining, the capital of Qinghai Province, China. It is located in Huzhu County, Haidong, about 30 kilometres (19 mi) east of downtown Xining. The airport began operation in 1991, and in October 2011 a new 3,800 meter long runway was built to replace the old one.[3][4]

Xinji (Chinese: 辛集; pinyin: Xīnjí) is a county-level city of Hebei Province, North China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Shijiazhuang. It is the easternmost county-level division of Shijiangzhuang. There are 8 towns (镇; zhèn) and 7 townships (乡; xiāng) under the administration of Xinji.

Xinjian (Chinese: 新建区; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Qū) is one of 6 urban districts of the prefecture-level city of Nanchang, the capital of Jiangxi Province, China, located on the western (left) bank of the Gan River. It consists of two disjoint sections to the north and south of Wanli and Qingshanhu districts.

Xinjian Subdistrict (Chinese: 新建街道; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Hunjiang District, Baishan, Jilin province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 7 residential communities and one special development zone under its administration.[2]

Xinjian Subdistrict (Chinese: 新建街道; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Changyi District, Jilin City, Jilin province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 3 residential communities under its administration.[2]

Xinjian Subdistrict (Chinese: 新建街道; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Yuci District, Jinzhong, Shanxi province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 9 residential communities under its administration.[2]

Xinjian Subdistrict (Chinese: 新建街道; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Ang'angxi District, Qiqihar, Heilongjiang province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 2 residential communities under its administration.[2]

Xinjian Subdistrict (Chinese: 新建街道; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Zhanqian District, Yingkou, Liaoning province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has six residential communities under its administration.[2]

Xinjian Township (simplified Chinese: 新建乡; traditional Chinese: 新建鄉; pinyin: Xīnjiàn Xiāng) is a township under the administration of Yingjing County, in central Sichuan, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 4 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinjiang (Uyghur: شىنجاڭ‎, SASM/GNC: Xinjang; Chinese: 新疆; pinyin: Xīnjiāng; alternately romanized as Sinkiang), officially the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region[8] (XUAR), is a formally autonomous region in Northwestern China. Being the largest province-level division of China and the 8th largest country subdivision in the world, Xinjiang spans over 1.6 million km2 (640,000 square miles).[1] A small part of Xinjiang is claimed by India, referring to it as "Aksai Chin". Xinjiang borders the countries of Mongolia (Bayan-Ölgii, Khovd and Govi-Altai Provinces), Russia (Altai Republic), Kazakhstan (East Kazakhstan and Almaty Provinces), Kyrgyzstan (Issyk Kul, Naryn and Osh Regions), Tajikistan (Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region), Afghanistan (Badakhshan Province), Pakistan (Gilgit Baltistan) and India (Ladakh and Jammu and Kashmir). The rugged Karakoram, Kunlun and Tian Shan mountain ranges occupy much of Xinjiang's borders, as well as its western and southern regions. Xinjiang also borders the Tibet Autonomous Region and the provinces of Gansu and Qinghai. The most well-known route of the historical Silk Road ran through the territory from the east to its northwestern border.

Xinjiang (Chinese: 新江; pinyin: Xīnjiāng) is a town under the administration of Yongning District, Nanning, Guangxi, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has one residential community and 8 villages under its administration.[2]
Xinjiang County (Chinese: 新绛县; pinyin: Xīnjiàng Xiàn), formerly Jiangzhou (Chinese: 绛州), lies in the municipal region of Yuncheng in the southwest of Shanxi province, China.

The county's area is approximately 600 km2. It is bordered by Wenxi County to the east and Jishan County to the west. Xiangning County to the northwest, Xiangfen County to the northeast, and Houma City to the east are all in Linfen Municipality.

Xinjiang Subdistrict (Chinese: 新疆街道; pinyin: Xīnjiāng Jiēdào) is a subdistrict in Pingfang District, Harbin, Heilongjiang province, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 4 residential communities under its administration.[2]

Xinjin County (simplified Chinese: 新津县; traditional Chinese: 新津縣; pinyin: Xīnjīn Xiàn; literally: 'new ford') is a county of Sichuan Province, China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Chengdu, the provincial capital. It borders the prefecture-level city of Meishan to the south.
Xinjing (Chinese: 新靖) is a town of Jingxi, Guangxi, China.[1] As of 2018[update], it has 9 residential communities and 21 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinle (simplified Chinese: 新乐; traditional Chinese: 新樂; pinyin: Xīnlè is a county-level city of Hebei Province, North China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Shijiazhuang.
Xinlitun (新立屯),or Hsin-li-t’un, is a town within Heishan County in Jinzhou prefecture, Liaoning, China. It's in the north east of the prefecture about 100 km west of Shenyang city.
Xinma (Chinese: 新馬車站; pinyin: Xīnmǎ Chēzhàn) is a railway station on the Taiwan Railways Administration Yilan line. It is located in Su'ao Township, Yilan County, Taiwan.

Xinmi (Chinese: 新密; pinyin: Xīnmì), formerly Mi County (simplified Chinese: 密县; traditional Chinese: 密縣; pinyin: Mì Xiàn), is a county-level city of Henan Province, South Central China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Zhengzhou.

The city of Xinmin (Chinese: 新民; pinyin: Xīnmín; Wade–Giles: Hsin-min) is a county-level city of Liaoning Province, Northeast China, it is under the administration of the prefecture-level city of Shenyang. It contains the westernmost point of and is by far the most spacious of the county-level divisions of Shenyang City.[2] Xinmin borders Faku County to the northeast, Shenbei New Area and Yuhong District to the east, Tiexi District to the southeast, and Liaozhong County to the south; it also borders the prefecture-level cities of Jinzhou to the west and Fuxin to the northwest.

Xinning County (Chinese: 新宁县; pinyin: Xīnníng Xiàn) is a county in the Province of Hunan, China, it is under the administration of Shaoyang City. Located on the south western margin of Hunan, the county is bordered to the northeast by Shaoyang County, to the northwest by Wugang City, to the west by Chengbu Autonomous County, to the south by Ziyuan County of Guangxi, to the east by Dong'an County. Xinning County covers 2,756.13 km2 (1,064.15 sq mi), as of 2015, it had a registered population of 649,700 and a permanent resident population of 574,100.[1] The county has 8 towns and 8 townships under its jurisdiction, the county seat is Jinshi (金石镇).[2]

Xinping Yi and Dai Autonomous County (Chinese: 新平彝族傣族自治县; pinyin: Xīnpíng Yízú Dǎizú Zìzhìxiàn) is an autonomous county located in the central part of Yunnan Province, China. It is the westernmost county-level division of the prefecture-level city of Yuxi.

Xinpu (Chinese: 新埔車站; Hanyu Pinyin: Xīnpù Chēzhàn; Tongyong Pinyin: Sinpù Chejhàn) is a railway station on the Taiwan Railways Administration West Coast line (Coastal line) located in Tongxiao Township, Miaoli County, Taiwan.[2]

Xinqiao (simplified Chinese: 新桥; traditional Chinese: 新橋; pinyin: Xīnqiáo; literally: 'new bridge') is a town of Anlong County in southwestern Guizhou province, China,[1] located 17 kilometres (11 mi) west-northwest of the county seat and 38 kilometres (24 mi) east of Xingyi, both of which can be reached by China National Highway 324. As of 2011[update], it has one residential community (居委会) and eight villages under its administration.[2]

Xinqiao (simplified Chinese: 新桥; traditional Chinese: 新橋; pinyin: Xīnqiáo; literally: 'new bridge') is a town under the administration of Xiangcheng City in southeastern Henan province, China,[1] located less than 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) north with the border with Anhui and 28 km (17 mi) south of downtown Xiangcheng. As of 2011[update], it has 29 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinqiao (simplified Chinese: 新桥; traditional Chinese: 新橋; pinyin: Xīnqiáo; literally: 'new bridge') is a town of Mouding County in north-central Yunnan province, China,[1] located 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) northeast of the county seat and 35 km (22 mi) north-northeast of Chuxiong City. As of 2011[update], it has 15 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinshao County (simplified Chinese: 新邵县; traditional Chinese: 新邵縣; pinyin: Xīnshào Xiàn) is a county in the Province of Hunan, China, it is under the administration of Shaoyang City. Located in central Hunan, the county is bordered to the north by Lianyuan City, Lengshuijiang City and Xinhua County, to the west by Longhui County, to the south by Shaoyang County and the city proper of Shaoyang. Xinshao County covers 1,763 km2 (681 sq mi),[1] as of 2015, it had a registered population of 828,100 and a permanent resident population of 769,700.[2] The county has 13 towns and 2 townships under its jurisdiction, the county seat is Niangxi (酿溪镇).[3][4]

Xinshe District (Chinese: 新社區; pinyin: Xīnshè Qū) is a rural district in Taichung, Taiwan.[1] It is also called "Taichung's back garden". The city is home to many military bases. However, the district's hillside houses were destroyed by 1999 Chi-Chi earthquake.

Xinshi (Chinese: 新市; pinyin: Xīnshì; literally: 'new city') is a town of west-central Changshou District in Chongqing Municipality, People's Republic of China,[1] located 67 kilometres (42 mi) northeast of central Chongqing. As of 2011[update], it has eight villages under its administration.[2]

Xinshi (Chinese: 新市; pinyin: Xīnshì; literally: 'new city') is a town under the administration of Mianzhu City in northern Sichuan, People's Republic of China,[1] located about 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) south-southwest of downtown Mianzhu. As of 2011[update], it has two residential communities (社区) and 13 villages under its administration.[2]

Xinshi (Chinese: 新市; pinyin: Xīnshì; literally: 'new city') is a town under the administration of Pingshan County in southeastern Sichuan province, China,[1] located about 31 kilometres (19 mi) west of the county seat on the southern (right) bank of the Min River, across which is Yunnan. As of 2011[update], it has two residential communities (社区) and 27 villages under its administration.[2]
